	<section id="presentation_audio" expanded="true">
		<audio id="narration01">
			<file play="true" bytes="50727" startpos="1" duration="149">a_02_02_01_010_01.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Imitative behavior provides children with the opportunity to practice and master new skills. Originally, psychologists referred to key aspects of this process as assimilation and accommodation.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration02">
			<file play="false" bytes="37791" startpos="1" duration="111">a_02_02_01_010_02.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">In assimilation, the child would see something new and then take parts of what he or she saw and reenact what had been observed as a self-initiated activity.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration03">
			<file play="false" bytes="26371" startpos="1" duration="78">a_02_02_01_010_03.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Later, the child would take the newly acquired information and use it to test variations on the theme.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration04">
			<file play="false" bytes="70015" startpos="1" duration="205">a_02_02_01_010_04.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">For example, a toddler sees a new type of sand toy in the sand pit at the playground and watches as a slightly older child pours sand into it. He runs up to the toy and imitates what he just saw. That imitation of the first child's use of the toy would be assimilation of a new play schema.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration05">
			<file play="false" bytes="131003" startpos="1" duration="382">a_02_02_01_010_05.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Later, he might decide to pour water or small stones through the machine instead. Or he might turn the machine upside down to see what happens if he puts sand in the other end. The results of all these little experiments allow him to construct a database of information about this type of sand toyâ€”first by assimilating what he saw the other child do and then by conducting his own experiments to try to understand how things like this might work. The accommodation aspect of this process is the part that leads to internalized changes and new knowledge.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
			<eventlist>
				<event type="PLAYHEAD_CHANGE" pos="1" result="SHOW" target="ref_icon01" result_param=""/>
			</eventlist>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration06">
			<file play="false" bytes="29923" startpos="1" duration="88">a_02_02_01_010_06.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">In this topic, the Key Message is that imitation has varying motivations and purposes at each stage of development.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
	</section>
